One of my patients sent me this video from @jillianmichaels about the new drug semaglutide. She has a gross misunderstanding of obesity and why people fail to lose weight along with how these trials are run.

I forgot to add in a quick segment about the fear of thyroid cancer. It is a very rare type of thyroid cancer that rats are predisposed to. There is no signal that this occurs in humans.

I have many patients on this medicine who finally feel they have a normal appetite. It’s not that they lack willpower, it’s because it’s physiology! Let me know what you think of the video.

node.text: Discussion with @soheefit and @bdccarpenter about obesity and dieting

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dr. Spencer Nadolsky on September 16, 2021. May be a Twitter screenshot of text that says 'Dr. SpInn Nadolsky @DrNadolsky "I've been in a calorie deficit for two years and have not lost weight!" -someone who was not in a calorie deficit'.

node.text:
I have to keep repeating this because every week I see a few people say they have been in a calorie deficit for a long period of time with no weight loss…. And it’s just not true.

It’s true they are probably trying. It’s true that they feel like they are constantly dieting. It’s true that that may be counting their calories. It’s true that they used some calculator that says they should be in a calorie deficit. What’s not true is that they are in a calorie deficit. If they were, they would be losing weight over a period of time (water fluctuations do occur).

Weight loss (what we really want is fat loss) occurs when you’re eating fewer calories than you burn. If you’re not losing weight/fat over the period of let’s say 2-4 weeks, it’s probably safe to say you’re not in a calorie deficit. Read the first paragraph in this post again.

There are a ton of variables to go through of why you can’t achieve this calorie deficit (hunger, inaccuracies in measuring, etc) but either way you’re not in a calorie deficit. This doesn’t mean you’re a bad person or an idiot or to blame etc. It’s just physiology.

So if this is you, it may be time to diagnose the issue at hand of why you aren’t able to do it. Or maybe it’s time to stop dieting. I can’t answer that without a history and knowing a lot more. ❤️oh and it’s not the damn carbs or insulin.

node.text:
Hey folks it’s not the carbs. It’s not the fat. It’s not the insulin. In order to lose fat and keep it off, you must eat fewer calories than you burn. This doesn’t mean you have to count calories. It doesn’t mean you have to go low carb or low fat. Either can work though.

So what should you do? Here are some general guidelines:

1. Eat mostly non-processed foods. I would suggest mostly vegetables and fruits and legumes with lean protein.

2. Drink mostly water, coffee, tea, and diet soda (if wanted but of course not needed). Basically drinks without calories.

3. Start finding which foods keep you fuller and satiated. Some may find higher carb starchy foods like potatoes work well. Some may find that lower carb higher fat foods work better (avocados). Some may enjoy a mix.

4. If still struggling, do a dietary audit and track how many calories you’re getting in. Weigh your food and figure out if portions are an issue.

5. Be conscious of bites and licks and tastes between meals. Sneaky calories. Adding butter and oils to pasta. It’s okay to do this but just be conscious of the added calories. Sauces can also add up.

Of course this alone may not be perfect but it’s a good start. I use the NIH bodyplanner tool to look at calorie recommendations but remember it’s just a starting point. We have our RP app and templates if you want us to tell you what to do. Can click on my link in bio and use coupon: START10

node.text:
Just a follow up from yesterday. Many folks choose grass fed beef just to get more omega 3s. It’s splitting hairs. You’re much better off looking for omega 3 content from fish which has magnitudes higher levels of omega 3 fatty acids. If you’re going to eat beef, I would go with the one that tastes best to you and not choose based on the small amount of omega 3 content differences. I’m sure my friend @thefarmbabe has much more information on this topic.

You can get omega 3s from non-fish sources as well like walnuts. The issue that some may bring up is that it comes in the form of alpha linolenic acid (ALA) which needs to be converted to EPA/DHA which can be found in fish without needing conversion. Algae supplementation is another option. Whether one actually needs to do this to be healthy I’m not sure. You can also supplement with fish oil, but this has fallen out of favor in recent years. It’s likely best to get better whole food sources.

Anyway, don’t get grass fed beef just for the omega 3 content. It’s silly.
